subsection.p:
If we write our linearization in matrix form, we have
            \begin{pmatrix}  du/dt \\ dv/dt \end{pmatrix}
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            f_x(x_0, y_0) \amp f_y(x_0, y_0) \\
            g_x(x_0, y_0) \amp g_y(x_0, y_0)
            \end{pmatrix}
            \begin{pmatrix}  u \\ v \end{pmatrix}.
        The matrix
            J
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            f_x(x_0, y_0)\amp f_y(x_0, y_0) \\
            g_x(x_0, y_0) \amp g_y(x_0, y_0)
            \end{pmatrix}
        is the Jacobian matrix of the system. We can now classify equilibrium solutions of nonlinear systems by examining the eigenvalues of the Jacobian matrix of the system or by using the trace-determinant plane. For example, if D =\det(J) \gt 0 and T =\trace(J) \lt 0, we have a sink. We can determine the sink to be spiral or nodal by examining whether (T, D) lies above or below the parabola T^2 = 4D in the trace-determinant plane.
